title: For Sale/Trade:  Henry E. Leman 1830’s Indian Rifle
postcontent: Henry E. Leman Indian Rifle - Fullstock. Manufacture date is believed to be mid-1830s. Features 1 1/16” x 30” long octagon barrel. .36 caliber. Full maple stock, double-trigger and brass furniture.I was given the Rifle by my uncle’s estate. The gun seems to be in quite good condition for being almost 190 years old. It is missing the ram rod.I had the gun looked at while in VA Beach by an antique gun expert. There does not appear to be any visible external markings on the gun, and he believed that they may be on the underside of the barrel. So without taking it apart there’s no way to confirm. In his opinion based on materials used and styling, he believed it to be a Leman production piece from the mid 1830’s. He valued it around $1,000. Since I have nothing to support it’s authenticity, I’m leaving it open to offers. It is an exceptional piece of history. I cannot make any claims as to whether it is safe to fire but it is solid. It might just be a great wallhanger. It is one of the heaviest rifles I’ve ever held. There are still percussion caps in the storage box in the cheek plate.My uncle has Cherokee heritage. Born in western VA. Not sure when he acquired the rifle. He would always talk about this old percussion gun he had but would never bring it out to show anyone. After his passing, we were going through his belongings and we found the rifle wrapped in a blanket. It was after his estate was settled that I acquired the piece. I’m not an antique gun person. Don’t really have a place to display it and it seems a shame to just keep it in my safe.Reasonable offers considered.Thanks for your interest.
